
                    <div
                      data-cnxml-to-html-ver="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                      data-type="page"
                      id="15be4435-4470-4cb9-b6ce-fdb871aba9f1"
                    >
                      <div data-type="abstract" id="[redacted for uniqueness]">
                        By the end of this section, you will be able to:
                        <ul>
                          <li>List common applications of radioactive isotopes</li>
                        </ul>
                      </div>

                      <p id="fs-idp54341648">
                        Radioactive isotopes have the same chemical properties as stable isotopes of the same element, but they emit radiation, which can be detected. If we replace one (or more) atom(s) with radioisotope(s) in a compound, we can track them by monitoring their radioactive emissions. This type of compound is called a
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="r"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >radioactive tracer</span> (or
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="r"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >radioactive label</span>). Radioisotopes are used to follow the paths of biochemical reactions or to determine how a substance is distributed within an organism. Radioactive tracers are also used in many medical applications, including both diagnosis and treatment. They are used to measure engine wear, analyze the geological formation around oil wells, and much more.
                      </p>

                      <p id="fs-idp247341312">
                        Radioisotopes have revolutionized medical practice (see
                        <a
                          class="target-chapter"
                          href="m-half-lives-for-several-radioactive-isotopes"
                        >Appendix M</a>
), where they are used extensively. Over 10 million nuclear medicine procedures and more than 100 million nuclear medicine tests are performed annually in the United States. Four typical examples of radioactive tracers used in medicine are technetium-99
