                      </div>

                      <p id="fs-idp240963344">
                        Radioisotopes can also be used, typically in higher doses than as a tracer, as treatment.
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="R"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >Radiation therapy</span> is the use of high-energy radiation to damage the DNA of cancer cells, which kills them or keeps them from dividing (
                        <a
                          class="autogenerated-content"
                          href="#CNX_Chem_21_05_RadTherapy"
                        >Figure 21.26</a>). A cancer patient may receive
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="e"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >external beam radiation therapy</span> delivered by a machine outside the body, or
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="i"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >internal radiation therapy (brachytherapy)</span> from a radioactive substance that has been introduced into the body. Note that
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="c"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >chemotherapy</span> is similar to internal radiation therapy in that the cancer treatment is injected into the body, but differs in that chemotherapy uses chemical rather than radioactive substances to kill the cancer cells.
                      </p>

                      <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_21_05_RadTherapy">
                        <figure
                          class="scaled-down"
                          data-id="CNX_Chem_21_05_RadTherapy"
                        >
